flowRoot.flowPara: Time spent and left of transient states in stationary populations
Any R code or LaTeX related to this work is available in a public repository, including while in development:
https://github.com/timriffe/TransientSymmetry

We give an intuitive proof that the distributions of time spent and left are equal within states in stationary populations. We hope that this relationship may inspire new measurement approaches, especially, with respect to the estimating unobserved onset of health conditions. We think that that researchers working with censored or truncated data or any kind of multistate models should be generally aware of this equality in case it may come in handy as a heuristic.

The transient tenure symmetry we describe here is also tractable in stable populations, but we have not investigated this extension in detail. Future research, potentially more sophisticated simulations, should aim to establish the impact of departures from stationarity and suggest bounds of usability for this relationship.
F. Villavicencio and T. Riffe (2016) Symmetries between life lived and left in finite stationary populations, Demographic Research. V. 34, pp 381-398
T. Riffe and N. Brouard (2018) Structure and dynamics of populations: The ‘years-to-live’ pyramid, national aspects and regional examples. Socarxiv. An English translation of:
N. Brouard (1986) Structure et dynamique des populations. La pyramide des années à vivre, aspects nationaux et exemples régionaux. Espace, Populations, Sociétés vol.4 n°2, pp. 157-168

flowRoot.flowPara: In stationary multistate populations, the distribution of individuals in a given state by time spent continuously in that state is identical to (or symmetrical to) the distribution by time left in that state. We aim to prove this symmetry.

This might be useful to know because if you can estimate one of these distributions then you can infer the other. Specifically, it might be helpful to devise a way to estimate the unobserved age pattern of onset for health conditions.

flowRoot.style: font-size:18px;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;font-weight:normal;font-stretch:normal;line-height:125%;letter-spacing:0px;word-spacing:0px;fill:#000000;fill-opacity:1;stroke:none;font-family:Liberation Sans;-inkscape-font-specification:Liberation Sans
flowRoot.flowPara: Symmetry between years lived and years left is a known property of single state stationary populations, the Brouard-Carey Equality. This equality has been helpful in biodemography and historical demography, where age is sometimes unobserved, but followup to death is possible.

That multistate stationary populations produce the expectation of a fixed multistate trajectory composition is known. We illustrate this point with an example, for clarity, because it is a property we use to prove a Brouard-Carey symmetry for states in multistate stationary populations.

episode. Over the episode, we click

flowRoot.flowPara: Once in stationary renewal, the probability of observing this very episode in exactly the same way is fixed in each time interval. If renewal is happening in lock-step with age (as in discrete Lexis steps), then we expect to see each time spent and time left value of this episode simultaneously, but over sequentially replicated life trajectories.
